</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="07FF3F02E47F226A692B0E70C1C3DF62" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="notes">
<paragraph id="3CD1ABAD2F51AE599F9D796E6CDFCCB0" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Note.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F65F5609C7FA67DAA59242E0A6A65BA7" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
A very distinctive species because of the winged stem, deeply 3-lobed leaves, much-branched, almost paniculate inflorescence and the aristate sepals. The white flowers are reported to be aromatic. Molecular sequencing using 
<emphasis id="8BF021C528157F484760B74CDB721D41" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">ITS</emphasis>
suggests a relationship with 
<taxonomicName id="42E2C8B60EC9CA86842638FD91985E47" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="costellata">
<emphasis id="3ED7BA716DD59F0A71C16692AAE5BD9B" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ipomoea costellata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and its allies but there is little superficial morphological similiarity apart from the aristate sepals and trilobed leaves.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
